### 10. RESPONSE VALIDATION AND SCHEMA

From `/packages/fal/src/fal-image-model.ts`:

```typescript
const falValidationErrorSchema = z.object({
  detail: z.array(
    z.object({
      loc: z.array(z.string()),
      msg: z.string(),
      type: z.string(),
    }),
  ),
});

const falHttpErrorSchema = z.object({
  message: z.string(),
});

const falErrorSchema = z.union([
  falValidationErrorSchema,
  falHttpErrorSchema,
]);

const falImageSchema = z.object({
  url: z.string(),
  width: z.number().nullish(),
  height: z.number().nullish(),
  content_type: z.string().nullish(),
  file_name: z.string().nullish(),
  file_size: z.number().nullish(),
});

const commonResponseSchema = z.object({
  timings: z.object({ inference: z.number().optional() }).optional(),
  seed: z.number().optional(),
  has_nsfw_concepts: z.array(z.boolean()).optional(),
  nsfw_content_detected: z.array(z.boolean()).optional(),
  // ...
});

const falImageResponseSchema = z
  .union([
    commonResponseSchema.extend({ images: z.array(falImageSchema) }),
    commonResponseSchema.extend({ image: falImageSchema }),
  ])
  .transform(v => ('images' in v ? v : { ...v, images: [v.image] }))
  .pipe(commonResponseSchema.extend({ images: z.array(falImageSchema) }));
```

**Pattern:**
- Define separate schemas for different response formats
- Support union types for variants
- Use `.transform()` to normalize responses
- Use `.pipe()` to ensure final format

